{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:34:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:34:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18577"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18577"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.03,0.33,0.33,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112010"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11309"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11615"},{"type":"tags","id":"11616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11620"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45864"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112010"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of pale patches on her chest, back, and arms. The patches are mildly itchy and become more noticeable when she develops a tan. She started the oral contraceptive pill five months ago for contraception. She has no significant medical history. She works as a personal trainer and spends considerable time exercising outdoors. She states her brother and her mother have similar pale patches on their skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple well-demarcated, hypopigmented macules with fine scale across her upper chest, back,  shoulders, and upper arms. Wood\u0027s light examination reveals yellow-green fluorescence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral terbinafine","Coal tar","Topical selenium sulfide","Topical clotrimazole","Topical hydrocortisone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of tinea versicolor (pityriasis versicolor), a common superficial fungal infection caused by \u003Cem\u003EMalassezia\u003C/em\u003E species. The characteristic findings include hypopigmented (or sometimes hyperpigmented) macules with fine scale, typically affecting the trunk and proximal upper limbs. The condition is more noticeable in summer or with sun exposure, as the affected areas do not tan normally. Hot and humid environments, malnutrition, oral contraceptives, diabetes mellitus, Cushing disease, immunodeficiency and pregnancy can predispose to the development of tinea versicolour. There is a genetic predisposition as well as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical selenium sulfide\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective first-line treatment for localised tinea versicolor. It can be applied as a shampoo or lotion, left on for 10 minutes, then rinsed off daily for one week, then weekly for maintenance if needed to prevent recurrence. It works by having both antifungal and keratolytic properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as this is a fungal infection rather than an inflammatory condition. Steroids could potentially worsen the infection by suppressing local immune responses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral terbinafine\u003C/strong\u003E is not the treatment of choice for tinea versicolor as it has poor activity against \u003Cem\u003EMalassezia\u003C/em\u003E species. It is more commonly used for dermatophyte infections such as tinea corporis or onychomycosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical clotrimazole\u003C/strong\u003E, while an effective antifungal, is not the most practical first-line treatment for tinea versicolor due to the typically large surface area involved. It would be more appropriate for localised dermatophyte infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoal tar\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for conditions like psoriasis and seborrhoeic dermatitis. It has no antifungal properties and would not be effective in treating tinea versicolor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to inform patients that the pigmentary changes may persist for weeks to months after successful treatment of the infection. Additionally, the condition has a high recurrence rate, and prophylactic treatment may be needed, particularly in humid climates or in patients who exercise frequently.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tinea versicolor is a superficial fungal infection caused by Malassezia species that presents with hypo- or hyperpigmented macules.","Topical selenium sulfide is an effective first-line treatment for localised tinea versicolor."],"references":["Leung AK, Barankin B, Lam JM, Leong KF, Hon KL. Tinea versicolor: an updated review. Drugs Context. 2022.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9677953/","Oakley A.  Pityriasis versicolour. DermNet NZ. 2021.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/pityriasis-versicolor"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18577"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-23T20:25:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-23T20:28:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11309"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112010"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta